  <section id="how-we-evaluate">
    <h2>How we evaluate</h2>
    <p>We researched current listings, compared manufacturer specs, and analyzed user-reported workflow patterns to score each grinder on six factors: grind consistency, burr quality, adjustment usability, grind speed, cleanup burden, and value. For this list, we also weighted espresso-fine range more heavily than on general filter-only pages, because many buyers under $100 are trying to get both pour-over and occasional espresso from one grinder.</p>
    <p>This roundup is based on researched comparisons rather than direct bench measurements. We prioritize consistency signals that matter in daily use: does the adjustment system repeat reliably, does the burr set produce manageable fines, and how much effort is required for a normal 18g dose? Those practical factors usually matter more than marketing claims about burr shape or premium coatings.</p>
    <p>When two grinders are close in cup quality, we break ties on friction: how fast you can switch brew methods, how messy the workflow gets, and how likely a beginner can get repeatable results in the first week.</p>
  </section>

